video_description: #greenscreen besties the jewish national fund is not what we think it is. As always, üîó in b!o for sources #üçâ #ecofriendly
Content: All right, my fellow Jewish Americans, let's talk about that beautiful tradition that we have that for only 18 dollars, you can plant a tree in Israel in someone's name. Because when I was growing up, that was such a huge deal. And if you're not at you, the biggest reasons that we do this are for the birth of a child, for when someone becomes a bar about Mitzvah, or even like to memorialize someone after they have passed. And besides, like how cool is it to have a literal tree planted in your name in the Jewish homeland? I mean, for a Jewish American kid, it's pretty freaking cool. And when I went to Israel on my eighth grade trip with my Jewish day school, they even took us to a spot where we got to physically place a tree sapling into the ground in our own honor. It was so cool. So a little bit of background tree planting is done through the Jewish National Fund or the JNF. It's a nonprofit that was founded in 1901 to buy and develop land in Palestine or at the time it was still Ottoman Syria. And since the JNF's creation, they have planted over 240 million trees in Israel. And it's been a commonly accepted way for Jews in the diaspora to build relationships with the land of Israel without physically living there. Amidstva, some might say. So whenever I heard the acronym JNF in the past, I had positive connotations. I didn't really think much about it until reading the ethnic cleansing of Palestine by Elon Pappay. Because early on in the book, he mentions JNF in the context of colonization. And immediately I was like, what? What's the tree people? Yep, the tree people. So later on, I was reading a part in the book about what happened to Palestinians after Israel declared independence in 1948. And here's where I like truly lost my mind. As we know, UN resolution wanted before called for the immediate repatriation of Palestinians, which Israel blatantly ignored. In the Arab Affairs Committee, which was created and run by Zionists, knew that they had to settle the Palestinian property strategically so that the whole world wouldn't turn against them. And one suggestion solution was, how about we sell it to the American Jews? According to international law, they couldn't sell the stolen land, so they had to come up with something else. So they suggested that perhaps that they could buy the land from the Arab that no longer wished to return. But that idea was struck down immediately by Joseph Whites, who was the head of the JNF at the time. You see, Whites had been very closely following Zionist colonization specifically of the rural areas of the land. And he worked really hard to make sure that as that land was colonized, all of it fell into JNF hands. So I'm quoting Whites word for word on what he suggested they do next. All we need is 400 tractors. Each tractor can cultivate 3,000 dunam, cultivating not just for the purpose of procuring food, but in order to prevent anyone returning to their lands. Land of lesser quality should be sold to private or public sectors. Members of the Arab Affairs Committee, who still had a little bit of humanity left, were opposed to this idea. And so they tried to find another solution. But before they could, Davi Bengorion got impatient. And so he decided to create a new committee of two to make the decision. And one of those two people was Joseph Whites. So of course, the decision they made focused on destruction and confiscation of the land. And it's insane to me because in Judaism, this is such a widely accepted form of gifting. And now that things have moved online, you can plant a tree in Israel for a multitude of reasons. Just at the click of a button. Check it out. Here's a pet certificate. And then we have the Coretta Scott King Forest certificate. And finally, we have the iTreeU certificate. I'm not quite sure that they ate with that one.

And besides, like how cool is it to have a literal tree planted in your name in the Jewish homeland? I mean, for a Jewish American kid, it's pretty freaking cool. And when I went to Israel on my eighth grade trip with my Jewish day school, they even took us to a spot where we got to physically place a tree sapling into the ground in our own honor. It was so cool. So a little bit of background tree planting is done through the Jewish National Fund or the JNF. It's a nonprofit that was founded in 1901 to buy and develop land in Palestine or at the time it was still Ottoman Syria. And since the JNF's creation, they have planted over 240 million trees in Israel. And it's been a commonly accepted way for Jews in the diaspora to build relationships with the land of Israel without physically living there. Amidstva, some might say. So whenever I heard the acronym JNF in the past, I had positive connotations. I didn't really think much about it until reading the ethnic cleansing of Palestine by Elon Pappay. So later on, I was reading a part in the book about what happened to Palestinians after Israel declared independence in 1948. And here's where I like truly lost my mind. In the Arab Affairs Committee, which was created and run by Zionists, knew that they had to settle the Palestinian property strategically so that the whole world wouldn't turn against them. And one suggestion solution was, how about we sell it to the American Jews? According to international law, they couldn't sell the stolen land, so they had to come up with something else. So they suggested that perhaps that they could buy the land from the Arab that no longer wished to return. But that idea was struck down immediately by Joseph Whites, who was the head of the JNF at the time. You see, Whites had been very closely following Zionist colonization specifically of the rural areas of the land. And he worked really hard to make sure that as that land was colonized, all of it fell into JNF hands. So I'm quoting Whites word for word on what he suggested they do next. All we need is 400 tractors. Each tractor can cultivate 3,000 dunam, cultivating not just for the purpose of procuring food, but in order to prevent anyone returning to their lands. Land of lesser quality should be sold to private or public sectors. Members of the Arab Affairs Committee, who still had a little bit of humanity left, were opposed to this idea. And so they tried to find another solution. But before they could, Davi Bengorion got impatient. And so he decided to create a new committee of two to make the decision. And one of those two people was Joseph Whites. So of course, the decision they made focused on destruction and confiscation of the land. Content: What does Israel have to do with Ramadan? Well, in Israel, 21% of the population is Arab, roughly 1.9 million Israeli Arabs. The majority of them are Muslims. They enjoy full civil rights, equality, and of course, freedom of religion. In addition to that, Arabic is considered the holy language in Islam as the Quran was written in Arabic. And in Israel, Hebrew and Arabic are the official languages in the state of Israel. But fine, we're talking about freedom of religion for Muslims in Israel and blah, blah, blah. But are Muslims safe and protected in Israel? Well, the Muslim population in Israel has increased about 10 fold since the state was established. From some 156,000 in 1949 to over 1.5 million today, there are over 400 mosques in Israel. 73 of them are located in Jerusalem alone. So not only Muslims are safe in Israel, but they are happy and thriving, and these are the facts. Muslims are part of the Israeli society. Many of them volunteer to join the army, become doctors, bank managers, judges, ministers, police officers, and more. As a Jew myself, I consider the Muslims my brothers and sisters. I love them. So Ramadan Mubarak, to all the Muslims celebrating, may we continue to come closer to one another, united for peace, united against radicalism and terrorism.

Content: My name is Muhammad. I'm 25 years old. I was born in Nazareth. What's currently going on in Israel? We're making a long story short. We're talking about a regime change. That's what's undergoing right now. How are these rallies responding? These rallies are responding in an amazing way. Hundreds of thousands of people are taken to the streets. And it is very, very powerful. And I hope it only inspires other people in other countries. How is the Arab society in your reactor so far? There's this straight line that connects the occupation. This discrimination against Arabs to the judicial coup that's happening right now. Everything is connected. And I think that the fact that a lot of the organizers of the protest movement who are refusing to at least publicly acknowledge this disconnection deters the masses from the Arab community to join. We don't have a problem with the essence of a Jewish country in a sense of a culturally Jewish country, a Jewish majority country. That's not the problem. The problem is with its foundations. What it means to be a Jewish country. Does it mean what Bangville and Vitalis Montritch want to offer us? Jewish supremacy? Or does it mean that this country is as Jewish just as America is unofficially Christian? And until these issues and these topics are talked about, I'm not hopeful that the Arab community will join in masses.

video_description: Every Muslim Should Watch This Video About Israel >> #Ramadan #Israel #Palestine
Content: What does Israel have to do with Ramadan? Well, in Israel, 21% of the population is Arab, roughly 1.9 million Israeli Arabs. The majority of them are Muslims. They enjoy full civil rights, equality, and of course, freedom of religion. In addition to that, Arabic is considered the holy language in Islam as the Quran was written in Arabic. And in Israel, Hebrew and Arabic are the official languages in the state of Israel. But fine, we're talking about freedom of religion for Muslims in Israel and blah, blah, blah. But are Muslims safe and protected in Israel? Well, the Muslim population in Israel has increased about 10 fold since the state was established. From some 156,000 in 1949 to over 1.5 million today, there are over 400 mosques in Israel. 73 of them are located in Jerusalem alone. So not only Muslims are safe in Israel, but they are happy and thriving, and these are the facts. Muslims are part of the Israeli society. Many of them volunteer to join the army, become doctors, bank managers, judges, ministers, police officers, and more. As a Jew myself, I consider the Muslims my brothers and sisters. I love them. So Ramadan Mubarak, to all the Muslims celebrating, may we continue to come closer to one another, united for peace, united against radicalism and terrorism.

That's what's undergoing right now. How are these rallies responding? These rallies are responding in an amazing way. Hundreds of thousands of people are taken to the streets. And it is very, very powerful. And I hope it only inspires other people in other countries. How is the Arab society in your reactor so far? There's this straight line that connects the occupation. This discrimination against Arabs to the judicial coup that's happening right now. Everything is connected. And I think that the fact that a lot of the organizers of the protest movement who are refusing to at least publicly acknowledge this disconnection deters the masses from the Arab community to join. We don't have a problem with the essence of a Jewish country in a sense of a culturally Jewish country, a Jewish majority country. That's not the problem. The problem is with its foundations. What it means to be a Jewish country. Does it mean what Bangville and Vitalis Montritch want to offer us? Jewish supremacy? Or does it mean that this country is as Jewish just as America is unofficially Christian? And until these issues and these topics are talked about, I'm not hopeful that the Arab community will join in masses.

video_description: Every Muslim Should Watch This Video About Israel >> #Ramadan #Israel #Palestine
Content: What does Israel have to do with Ramadan? Well, in Israel, 21% of the population is Arab, roughly 1.9 million Israeli Arabs. The majority of them are Muslims. They enjoy full civil rights, equality, and of course, freedom of religion. In addition to that, Arabic is considered the holy language in Islam as the Quran was written in Arabic. And in Israel, Hebrew and Arabic are the official languages in the state of Israel. But fine, we're talking about freedom of religion for Muslims in Israel and blah, blah, blah. But are Muslims safe and protected in Israel? Well, the Muslim population in Israel has increased about 10 fold since the state was established. From some 156,000 in 1949 to over 1.5 million today, there are over 400 mosques in Israel. 73 of them are located in Jerusalem alone. So not only Muslims are safe in Israel, but they are happy and thriving, and these are the facts. Muslims are part of the Israeli society. Many of them volunteer to join the army, become doctors, bank managers, judges, ministers, police officers, and more. As a Jew myself, I consider the Muslims my brothers and sisters. I love them. So Ramadan Mubarak, to all the Muslims celebrating, may we continue to come closer to one another, united for peace, united against radicalism and terrorism.

video_description: Every Muslim Should Watch This Video About Israel >> #Ramadan #Israel #Palestine
Content: What does Israel have to do with Ramadan? Well, in Israel, 21% of the population is Arab, roughly 1.9 million Israeli Arabs. The majority of them are Muslims. They enjoy full civil rights, equality, and of course, freedom of religion. In addition to that, Arabic is considered the holy language in Islam as the Quran was written in Arabic. And in Israel, Hebrew and Arabic are the official languages in the state of Israel. But fine, we're talking about freedom of religion for Muslims in Israel and blah, blah, blah. But are Muslims safe and protected in Israel? Well, the Muslim population in Israel has increased about 10 fold since the state was established. From some 156,000 in 1949 to over 1.5 million today, there are over 400 mosques in Israel. 73 of them are located in Jerusalem alone. So not only Muslims are safe in Israel, but they are happy and thriving, and these are the facts. Muslims are part of the Israeli society. Many of them volunteer to join the army, become doctors, bank managers, judges, ministers, police officers, and more. As a Jew myself, I consider the Muslims my brothers and sisters. I love them. So Ramadan Mubarak, to all the Muslims celebrating, may we continue to come closer to one another, united for peace, united against radicalism and terrorism.

Content: The Merkava Tank is an impressive piece of military machinery that was first introduced in 1979 by the Israeli Defense Forces. This beast of a tank is not just any ordinary tank, it was designed with a focus on crew safety and survivability. One of the most unique features of the Merkava Tank is its design. Unlike most other tanks that have the engine located at the back, the Merkava places the engine at the front of the tank, which provides additional protection for the crew in the event of an attack. The crew sits behind the engine, which acts as a shield to protect them from incoming fire. The Merkava Tank is also equipped with a powerful 120mm smoothbore cannon that is capable of firing a variety of ammunition types, including armor piercing and high explosive rounds. This cannon is incredibly accurate and can hit targets from several kilometers away.

Content: It's not just a couple soldiers that are bad soldiers or that enact violent occupation on Palestinians, but it's actually a whole system, system of violence, of pulling people into the army and making them work for the occupation and for oppressing Palestinians. Militarism in Israel is very entrenched in society and the military is like some golden goose that you're not allowed to touch, you're allowed to criticize the government, you're allowed to go out for gay rights for women's rights, but when it comes to criticizing military action against Palestinians or other oppressed communities, this is totally out of the norm. You cannot speak against the military because it's so entrenched in society. Like I said, a lot of conversations start with the military and because most people did serve, it's seen as this kind of thing that everyone needs the past in order to become an Israeli. Do you know if there are any long-term repercussions that come from refusing to serve a long conscientious grounds? Going out publicly and talking about refusing service, there is a huge social cost. I have the privilege to come out publicly, I have a supportive family and supportive friends, but a lot of refusesers don't have these supportive nets. It can cost friendships, but if someone doesn't respect me for my opinions and my beliefs, then I do not see friendship with them. What do you hope it's going to do in terms of the wider peace movement, and how do you hope to change people's minds? I hope to get to as many Israeli youth as possible and tell them that there is another option. Serving is not something that's going to happen forever and the army needs to change for there to be an actual solution in this place. We need to realize that non-violence is something normal. It's normal to non-violence and it's normal to want a solution here and that there are seven million Palestinians here and we need to acknowledge that fact that they're not going anywhere and live with them.

##Urgent #Alert #israelidefenseforces #Gaza
Content: Attention citizens of Gaza, listen carefully. This is an urgent military advisory from the Israel Defense Forces. For your immediate safety, we urge all residents of Northern Gaza and Gaza City to temporarily relocate south. Let me repeat, we urge all residents of Northern Gaza and Gaza City to relocate south immediately. This is a temporary measure. Moving back to Northern Gaza will be possible once the intense hostilities end. Hamas puts your life in danger by placing weapons and forces within civilians area in Gaza, including schools, masks and hospitals. The impending IDF operation is said to neutralize these threats of Hamas with precision and intensity. Humanity remains haunted by the massacre unleashed by Hamas on October 7th. A massacre of innocent lives is really men, women, children and babies were beheaded, executed, raped and burnt alive. We won't forget that. And the kidnapping of over 200 Israelis we will not forget. With the residents of Northern Gaza and Gaza City, your window to act is closing. Move south. For your own safety, move south. This is not a mere precaution. It is an urgent plea for the safety of the civilians in Gaza.

Content: The Merkava Tank is an impressive piece of military machinery that was first introduced in 1979 by the Israeli Defense Forces. This beast of a tank is not just any ordinary tank, it was designed with a focus on crew safety and survivability. One of the most unique features of the Merkava Tank is its design. Unlike most other tanks that have the engine located at the back, the Merkava places the engine at the front of the tank, which provides additional protection for the crew in the event of an attack. The crew sits behind the engine, which acts as a shield to protect them from incoming fire. The Merkava Tank is also equipped with a powerful 120mm smoothbore cannon that is capable of firing a variety of ammunition types, including armor piercing and high explosive rounds. This cannon is incredibly accurate and can hit targets from several kilometers away.

video_description: üü† The first day in the Israel Defense Forces is not what you think it is >> #israel #idf
Content: When I joined the Israeli Army, they deemed, first of all, give me a weapon and be like, okay, if you see somebody that looks like an Arab, you know what to do. Of course not, but it's insane that some people actually believe these lies. Your first day in the Israeli Friends Forces, you get this small booklet that's called the IDF Code of Ethics. And it's called in Hebrew Guwah Zal, Spirit of the IDF. And if, first of all, learn how to behave like a human being, you learn how to treat your enemy. And only then, you are taught how to defend your country physically, actually. And I also served as a combat medic. So when you're a combat medic, you take an oath actually to treat your enemies. And I've done that. Actually 90% of the people that I've treated during my military service were not Israelis. They were either Syrians or Palestinians.

Content: The Merkava Tank is an impressive piece of military machinery that was first introduced in 1979 by the Israeli Defense Forces. This beast of a tank is not just any ordinary tank, it was designed with a focus on crew safety and survivability. One of the most unique features of the Merkava Tank is its design. Unlike most other tanks that have the engine located at the back, the Merkava places the engine at the front of the tank, which provides additional protection for the crew in the event of an attack. The crew sits behind the engine, which acts as a shield to protect them from incoming fire. The Merkava Tank is also equipped with a powerful 120mm smoothbore cannon that is capable of firing a variety of ammunition types, including armor piercing and high explosive rounds. This cannon is incredibly accurate and can hit targets from several kilometers away.

Under the new guidelines, applicants would have to sign a declaration that they recognize Israel's right to exist and condemn any effort directed against the existence of the state of Israel. The move has to receive wide support from the political class in Germany, with many of the country's 15 other states expected to implement similar rules. Supporters say it will combat antisemitism and highlights Germany's historical responsibility to Israel and its security. But critics say its vague language will be misused to clamp down on legitimate criticism of Israel. Content: The German state of Saxony Unholt has introduced a controversial Israel law which states that if you want to be a German citizen, you must support Israel's existence. Under the new guidelines, applicants would have to sign a declaration that they recognize Israel's right to exist and condemn any effort directed against the existence of the state of Israel. The move has to receive wide support from the political class in Germany, with many of the country's 15 other states expected to implement similar rules. Supporters say it will combat antisemitism and highlights Germany's historical responsibility to Israel and its security. But critics say its vague language will be misused to clamp down on legitimate criticism of Israel. They also argue that it will do little to actually combat antisemitism, as Cremson's six regularly show that homegrown white supremacy far exceeds any threat posed by foreign sources.

But since this isn't the first time that Israeli's bombing Gaza, why now? Why this moment? Because the amount of casualties has reached catastrophic proportions. And even though we're in a temporary ceasefire or a pauser, whatever you want to call it right now, it seems like it's not going to end anytime soon. Israeli soldiers make mocking TikTok videos on top of the ruins of Palestinian homes in Gaza. Why am I doing this now? Because more than ever, it's clear to me now that in Israel peace is not the goal. And I don't know if it ever was. And when I think back on my childhood and all the times we spent running in and out of the bomb shelter, all the times my parents were worried about us, all the time I spent worrying while putting on a brave face like we were encouraged to. I feel like it's the kind of state that doesn't care about its own people. And I'm not even talking about all the torture, abuse and humiliation inflicted upon Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza, or Palestinians with Israeli citizenship that Israel loves to use as some sort of proof that it's not in the part-life state. I'm talking about the way Israel treats its own people. But I think I know why it took me so long. Israel spends so much time and money inciting its own people against each other, family members, friends, neighbors. This decision is going to affect my life, my ability to visit the place where I grew up. It's going to affect my relationship with my family, my relationships with the people closest to me, not just there, but here in Canada. I spent the past few weeks crying over witnessing horrific heartbreaking f***ing death and pain, but also grieving over the possibility that I may lose my relationship with my family. Everything that led to this decision, a process that led to this decision was filled with pain and anger and grief. But this decision is necessary. I'm done.

Content: There are currently 22 countries in the Arab League, but what if they were to United as one? The Arab League would be home to over 406 million people beating out the population of the United States and making it the world's third most populous country. The Arab League would be huge spanning 5 million square miles or 13 million square kilometers and would be larger than both the United States and Canada and would be about the size of Antarctica. Overall, this would make it the world's second largest country. It would have a GDP of around $2.44 trillion making it the world's eighth largest economy. The Arab League would also have a GDP per capita of about $6,000 making it most comparable to police, Armenia and Tulu. As for our capital city, Cairo is the most likely option as it's the current location of the Arab League's headquarters.

video_description: The oslo accords and their reprecussions.  Further reading preventing palestine seth anziska  Neoliberal apartheid andy clarno  Brokers of deceit rashid khalidi. #freepalestine #oslo #bds
Content: This photo depicts one of the most significant moments in the peace process between Israel Palestine. Now if you've never seen it before, on the right hand side is Yasser Adafat, the leader of the Palestinian Liberation Organization, also known by the initialism the PLO. On the left is the Labour Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, and in the middle is Bill Clinton, the then American president. What they effectively set in motion here was the Oslo I and Oslo II Accords. Now the photos from the Oslo I Accord, however this led to the Oslo II Accord. Now the second Oslo Accords was the significant one because it was the one that established area A, the area that would be under Palestinian civilian and security control, area B in the West Bank, this is where that would be placed under Palestinian control and Israeli security authority, and area C comprised 60% of the remaining West Bank that would be under full Israeli control. The other thing that the Oslo Accords gave the Palestinian people was the Palestinian authority or the PA. Now the PA is effectively a form of limited self-rule in the occupied territories for the Palestinian people, and the reason that this was so significant was because they were allowed for the first time to hold democratic elections and have a representative that Israel effectively respected. But the Oslo Accords were not what they seemed, they were not this significant moment with regards to a step towards peace for the Palestinian people. In reality, the PLO had betrayed the Palestinian people for their own interests, and also the Palestinian authority, this organization that was meant to give the Palestinian people some form of self-government is an organization that is largely benevolent to Israel and constitutes a new tool of colonial control over the West Bank because of the fact that the PA get all of their funding through Israel and Israel can choose to withhold it wherever it sees fit, meaning that the PA will do things like arrest Palestinian activists when Israel asks them to. But the Oslo Accords also harm the Palestinians for another reason, because the PLO accepted something called an interim agreement, and effectively what would be done according to Israel is that issues such as settlements, the right of return of refugees, what would be done with East Jerusalem amongst other things would be sorted within five years. We are now 30 years after the Oslo Accords were first signed, and nothing has seemingly changed, and it doesn't look like it will. In fact, the situation is worsened, and Israeli control over the West Bank is only growing. The reason the Arifat can be seen as betraying his people is because the Oslo Accords were not the only communications going on between the Israelis and the Palestinians at this time. The lead negotiators and the best negotiators from Palestine had actually been meeting the Israelis since 1992 and into 1993 in Madrid and Washington under an American-sponsored initiative in order to deal with the issues. These negotiators were much better, and they wouldn't let the issue of settlements carry on. They basically said that they would not negotiate with the Israelis with their hard-line position of effectively rejecting the idea of stopping settlements and ignoring the most important issues for them. Arifat was well aware that his influence was waning, his expulsion to Jordan and then to Lebanon and then to Tunisia had marginalized the PLO as a force. Islamic politics was growing within Gaza, and within the West Bank there was a new emerging leadership of young people founded from the Interfada. Arifat had also made the decision to support Saddam Hussein during the Gulf War, which had further damaged his and the PLO's legitimacy. So when this opportunity came up for him to talk to the Israelis directly and perhaps forge some kind of peace, he lapped at it and he was not able to avoid the pitfalls that the negotiators at Washington and Madrid had made well-sure to not agree to anything with Israel that would directly harm the Palestinian people. Joseph Mossad called the Oslo Accords the right for the Palestinian people to dispose of themselves. He effectively called it the end of the Palestinian chances and hopes for a state because ultimately what they accepted was Israel's right to colonize them. The PLO's behavior and Arifat's obsession with becoming a more significant figure led to the destruction of the hopes of a viable Palestinian state.

video_description: David Hearst, Middle East Eye editor-in-chief, argues that the Oslo Accords, once heralded as a peace-making mechanism, have instead perpetuated Israeli occupation. #Palestine #Israel #LearnOnTikTok #OsloAccords #GEOPolitics
Content: It is painfully clear that the prospect of creating a Palestinian state alongside one that defines itself as Jewish is zero. There are 700,000 settlers in the West Bank in East Jerusalem, and not an Israeli politician or movement in sight who is prepared to remove them. Quite the contrary, annexation exists at two speeds, creeping annexation tolerated by a broad spectrum of the Israeli political elite from the centre to the right, and annexation tomorrow as proposed by the National Religious Movement. This force is in the driving seat. So why does the international community continue to advocate for a two-state solution? When the Orslo Accords have essentially become unattainable? The short answer is that while Oslo is a path to peace is clearly dead, as a formula for maintaining the occupation, Oslo is alive and well. Just think for a moment, what would happen if Oslo were abandoned? The Palestinian President would resign and call elections. Those elections would be free and fair. Neither Israel nor Washington could cast a veto over the process or the outcome. Fatter would probably lose in the West Bank, but could win in Gaza. It would soon become clear that the best hope of all the Palestinian factions would be to form a government of national unity. But Palestinians would actually have a leadership, they elected. Not only would the PAB reinvigorate it, but so too would all the other bodies whose life has been sucked out of them. The PNC and the PLO. The new Palestinian leadership would stop security cooperation with Israel, which is a euphemism for letting soldiers undercover squads roam all over the territory that they control. The forces under the PAs control could then come face to face with Israeli soldiers and settlers, especially if the PAA did its job and actually defended Arab towns from settler attacks. Israel would have to start treating the PAA with respect. Not simply as another arm of occupation. If Oslo were abandoned, the international community couldn't threaten to cut off PAA funds because they would be damaging the formation of a Palestinian state, which they then would have to recognize. Now, do you seriously see all that happening? I for one don't. And that's the answer to the question of why a two-state solution still lives on in the bosom of every government in Europe, and the US and around the world. But let us be clear. Oslo exists today not as a peace process. That can only come when the occupation becomes too costly for the occupiers. Only then will they start to negotiate. When that happens, there can only be one solution. One state for all its peoples with equal rights, only then will the occupation, the nightmare of occupation be over.

video_description: The Oslo Accords were supposed to bring peace between Israel and Palestine when the first accord was signed in 1993 but why is Palestine still occupied 30 years later?  #LearnOnTikTok #Palestine #Israel
Content: Did you know this peaceful handshake between Israel and Palestinian leadership was awarded with a noble peace prize? Yet 30 years later peace seems like a distant... Ladies and gentlemen, we kindly ask that you remain seated during a document signing. The first of the Oslo Accords was signed on 13th September 1993. It should have marked the beginning of the end to the Israeli occupation of Gaza and the West Bank. We have been granted the great privilege of witnessing this victory for peace. Just as the Jewish people this week celebrate the dawn of a new year, let us all go from this place to celebrate the dawn of a new era. After a year of secret meetings in the Norwegian capital Oslo, after which the Accords were named, a plan was established for Israel to withdraw from parts in the West Bank and Gaza. Persons were also made to transfer governing duties to a Palestinian interim government, which later resulted in the creation of the Palestinian Authority. Occupy Palestine was divided in three areas. A. Under full Palestinian control. B. Civil control and Israel and Palestine would have joined security control. And C. would be under control of Israel except over Palestinians. Both parties were given five years to follow up on the plan. Afterwards, negotiations were set to reach permanent decisions on unresolved issues. A year after signing the Oslo Accords, the noble peace prize was awarded to former Palestinian Authority President Yasir Hadafant. Former Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Perez and former Prime Minister of Israel Yitzhak Rabin for their efforts to create peace in the Middle East. However, the Oslo Peace process quickly entered a cycle of failed negotiations until it ultimately collapsed during the 2000 Camp David summit and the second in Tifago. Afterwards, attempts were made to restart negotiations towards a two-state solution, but they never resulted into conclusive agreements. 30 years later, Palestine is still illegally occupied by Israel and Israeli settlers frequently construct new settlements in occupied Palestine under protection of the Israeli army. Content: This photo depicts one of the most significant moments in the peace process between Israel Palestine. Now if you've never seen it before, on the right hand side is Yasser Adafat, the leader of the Palestinian Liberation Organization, also known by the initialism the PLO. On the left is the Labour Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, and in the middle is Bill Clinton, the then American president. What they effectively set in motion here was the Oslo I and Oslo II Accords. Now the photos from the Oslo I Accord, however this led to the Oslo II Accord. Now the second Oslo Accords was the significant one because it was the one that established area A, the area that would be under Palestinian civilian and security control, area B in the West Bank, this is where that would be placed under Palestinian control and Israeli security authority, and area C comprised 60% of the remaining West Bank that would be under full Israeli control. The other thing that the Oslo Accords gave the Palestinian people was the Palestinian authority or the PA. Now the PA is effectively a form of limited self-rule in the occupied territories for the Palestinian people, and the reason that this was so significant was because they were allowed for the first time to hold democratic elections and have a representative that Israel effectively respected. But the Oslo Accords were not what they seemed, they were not this significant moment with regards to a step towards peace for the Palestinian people. In reality, the PLO had betrayed the Palestinian people for their own interests, and also the Palestinian authority, this organization that was meant to give the Palestinian people some form of self-government is an organization that is largely benevolent to Israel and constitutes a new tool of colonial control over the West Bank because of the fact that the PA get all of their funding through Israel and Israel can choose to withhold it wherever it sees fit, meaning that the PA will do things like arrest Palestinian activists when Israel asks them to. But the Oslo Accords also harm the Palestinians for another reason, because the PLO accepted something called an interim agreement, and effectively what would be done according to Israel is that issues such as settlements, the right of return of refugees, what would be done with East Jerusalem amongst other things would be sorted within five years. We are now 30 years after the Oslo Accords were first signed, and nothing has seemingly changed, and it doesn't look like it will. In fact, the situation is worsened, and Israeli control over the West Bank is only growing. The reason the Arifat can be seen as betraying his people is because the Oslo Accords were not the only communications going on between the Israelis and the Palestinians at this time. The lead negotiators and the best negotiators from Palestine had actually been meeting the Israelis since 1992 and into 1993 in Madrid and Washington under an American-sponsored initiative in order to deal with the issues. These negotiators were much better, and they wouldn't let the issue of settlements carry on. They basically said that they would not negotiate with the Israelis with their hard-line position of effectively rejecting the idea of stopping settlements and ignoring the most important issues for them. Arifat was well aware that his influence was waning, his expulsion to Jordan and then to Lebanon and then to Tunisia had marginalized the PLO as a force. Islamic politics was growing within Gaza, and within the West Bank there was a new emerging leadership of young people founded from the Interfada. Arifat had also made the decision to support Saddam Hussein during the Gulf War, which had further damaged his and the PLO's legitimacy. So when this opportunity came up for him to talk to the Israelis directly and perhaps forge some kind of peace, he lapped at it and he was not able to avoid the pitfalls that the negotiators at Washington and Madrid had made well-sure to not agree to anything with Israel that would directly harm the Palestinian people. Joseph Mossad called the Oslo Accords the right for the Palestinian people to dispose of themselves. He effectively called it the end of the Palestinian chances and hopes for a state because ultimately what they accepted was Israel's right to colonize them. The PLO's behavior and Arifat's obsession with becoming a more significant figure led to the destruction of the hopes of a viable Palestinian state.

The first intifada erupted in the late 1980s as a nonviolent form of collective disobedience with an emphasis on strikes and boycotts as a way of resisting Israeli oppression. Content: There's been a lot of talk lately about the term intifada. Long live the intifada. Intifada. Intifada revolution. There seems to be a lot of confusion about what this term does mean and what it doesn't mean. You understand that this call for intifada is to commit genocide against the Jewish people. Before we break it down, let's get one thing straight. Intifada is not a call for the genocide of the Jewish people and anyone who tells you that is lying to you. Intifada is an Arabic word that literally means to shake off. For Palestinians, it signifies uprising and revolution, a shaking off of oppression. Some Palestinian intifadas or uprisings have taken both nonviolent and violent paths towards resisting Israeli-seller colonialism and occupation. The first intifada erupted in the late 1980s as a nonviolent form of collective disobedience with an emphasis on strikes and boycotts as a way of resisting Israeli oppression. In response, Israel cracked down on the protests, criminalizing and closing down universities and implementing its breaking the bone strategy. Ironically, despite Palestinian nonviolent protests, their oppression intensified. In 2000, the second intifada erupted after years of a stalled peace process and rapidly increasing settlement expansion on Palestinian land. Unlike its predecessor, the second intifada did involve violence and was marked by suicide bombings and young Palestinians taking up arms against their oppressors. It's important to clarify that unlike what many people are saying, these acts of violence didn't take place simply because of some deep-seated hatred towards Jews. They happened because after years of violent repression by the Israeli state against Palestinians that went unchanged by peaceful protests and political negotiations, many saw no other option than to meet state violence with violence. Of course, it's not in the best interest of Zionists, the Israeli lobby and the politicians that they fund to properly contextualize terms like intifada because if they did, then you would spend less time worrying about a genocidal chant and more time worrying about an actual genocide that's taking place right now.

And today's existential enemy for Israel, and it is existential, is not really Hamas or the Palestinians, it's Iran and all the Iranian proxies, including Hamas. Iran and its proxies want to annihilate Israel and they are strong. And this war between Israel and Hamas probably would have already spread further, if not for the help of the United States, which is strategically bombing Iranian proxy targets in Iraq and elsewhere. Israel can no longer do it alone. And when this war ends, Hamas will be gone from governance, but Hamas will still be present in Gaza and Iran will still be a potent force trying to annihilate Israel. When this war ends, Israel will be weak and exhausted. I'm not happy about that. That's just the way it is. And when this war ends, Palestine will be weak and exhausted. About one-third of its populace will be living in rubble. And thousands of innocent civilians, Israeli, Palestinian, will have died. And if it's true that peace is really only possible in this region when both sides are weak and exhausted, it will be the best opportunity for peace. I'm not saying it's going to happen, but it will be the best opportunity for peace in the Middle East in 20 years.

Content: Did you know that it is only one time in the history of the world where Israel and Palestine actually made peace? That's right, the Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat shook the hand of the Israeli prime minister Yisra Krabim in front of the entire world and they agreed on peace in the Middle East. It happened 30 years ago in 1993. No one invited both sides to Oslo and they started negotiating. For the first time Palestine recognized Israel and Israel recognized Palestine. They started working out on the details, orders, refugees, business between the two countries, security for both the Israelis and the Palestinians. It was going so well they signed another peace treaty in 1995. Yasser Arafat received together the Nobel Peace Prize. For everybody around the world that was it, peace was on the way until something terrible happened. An extremist in Israel took the life of the Israeli prime minister, then Palestinian extremists jumped on the occasion and started terror attacks to cause more chaos. This trust between both sides started rising and eventually the Oslo agreement was put on pause forever. This story is full of sadness but it's also full of hope. It shows that what most Palestinians in Israel these actually want is peace. It's the extremists, the Palestinian extremists and the Israeli extremists who want to destroy everything and who only care about themselves that are responsible for the war. This handshake that happened 30 years ago is proof that Israelis and Palestinians can see eye to eye and respect each other. It's proof that there are people who believe a Palestinian state and an Israeli state can exist together. It's proof that peace is possible in the Middle East.

Content: So what do I think about what's happening at Rafa? I try to not talk actually that much about what's happening in the Middle East on social media because the level of a conversation on social media about the Middle East is almost always terrible and infantile, always side blaming. And I tend to like to be constructive, which is not what social media is usually about. So how can anyone be constructive about what's happening during this Israel Hamas war and what's going to happen in Rafa? The war is a huge human tragedy. Everyone knew beforehand that it would be a huge human tragedy and no, it is not genocide. It is a war in an urban area. Everyone knew that there would be tragic loss of human innocent life. And I personally, partly because of that, was not in favor of this invasion, but I also understood why it was taking place. The Israeli people overwhelmingly wanted Hamas eliminated taken out by the root. And in this war, a battle in Rafa was inevitable. So where do we go from here? Well, right now there is active and productive. I know people would say no, it's not productive, but it is negotiation taking place to establish a temporary. And yeah, it will likely be temporary ceasefire. It's a ceasefire that everyone needs Palestinians need aid. Israel needs some hostages return. They should have all of them return. And yeah, Hamas is planning on what to do next. It needs time for that planning. And my guess, and I think it's a good guess, is that there will be a ceasefire because all parties need it. And then likely there will be a battle in Rafa. Six weeks time will allow many Palestinians to leave Rafa and Hamas will lose that battle. I hope quickly. And after that, there will be more negotiations. And I don't know what will happen as a result of those, but I do know that there are major parties working for peace in the region. Saudis, United States, they're going to be squeezing both Israel and Palestine. I hope for the good of all people in their region that they succeed.

That's what makes that panel discussion so good. Am I bias? Everyone knows is Israel, right? That's where most of my family lives. But I do want peace. I want this horrific fighting to stop this month's fighting and fighting forever. And reading that panel discussion I was left with the impression that peace will come between Israel and Palestine only when both sides are weak and exhausted. And you may think I am delusional, but we are getting to the point where both sides are weak and completely exhausted. Israel is in fact weaker now than any time in my lifetime. It is weaker and less secure than it has been since 1948. Hundreds of thousands of Israelis have had to leave their border towns because they're no longer safe. That's never happened before. And today's existential enemy for Israel, and it is existential, is not really Hamas or the Palestinians, it's Iran and all the Iranian proxies, including Hamas. Iran and its proxies want to annihilate Israel and they are strong. And this war between Israel and Hamas probably would have already spread further, if not for the help of the United States, which is strategically bombing Iranian proxy targets in Iraq and elsewhere. Israel can no longer do it alone. And when this war ends, Hamas will be gone from governance, but Hamas will still be present in Gaza and Iran will still be a potent force trying to annihilate Israel. When this war ends, Israel will be weak and exhausted. I'm not happy about that. That's just the way it is. And when this war ends, Palestine will be weak and exhausted. About one-third of its populace will be living in rubble. And thousands of innocent civilians, Israeli, Palestinian, will have died. And if it's true that peace is really only possible in this region when both sides are weak and exhausted, it will be the best opportunity for peace. I'm not saying it's going to happen, but it will be the best opportunity for peace in the Middle East in 20 years.

Content: Did you know that it is only one time in the history of the world where Israel and Palestine actually made peace? That's right, the Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat shook the hand of the Israeli prime minister Yisra Krabim in front of the entire world and they agreed on peace in the Middle East. It happened 30 years ago in 1993. No one invited both sides to Oslo and they started negotiating. For the first time Palestine recognized Israel and Israel recognized Palestine. They started working out on the details, orders, refugees, business between the two countries, security for both the Israelis and the Palestinians. It was going so well they signed another peace treaty in 1995. Yasser Arafat received together the Nobel Peace Prize. For everybody around the world that was it, peace was on the way until something terrible happened. An extremist in Israel took the life of the Israeli prime minister, then Palestinian extremists jumped on the occasion and started terror attacks to cause more chaos. This trust between both sides started rising and eventually the Oslo agreement was put on pause forever. This story is full of sadness but it's also full of hope. It shows that what most Palestinians in Israel these actually want is peace. It's the extremists, the Palestinian extremists and the Israeli extremists who want to destroy everything and who only care about themselves that are responsible for the war. This handshake that happened 30 years ago is proof that Israelis and Palestinians can see eye to eye and respect each other. It's proof that there are people who believe a Palestinian state and an Israeli state can exist together. It's proof that peace is possible in the Middle East.

Content: So what do I think about what's happening at Rafa? I try to not talk actually that much about what's happening in the Middle East on social media because the level of a conversation on social media about the Middle East is almost always terrible and infantile, always side blaming. And I tend to like to be constructive, which is not what social media is usually about. So how can anyone be constructive about what's happening during this Israel Hamas war and what's going to happen in Rafa? The war is a huge human tragedy. Everyone knew beforehand that it would be a huge human tragedy and no, it is not genocide. It is a war in an urban area. Everyone knew that there would be tragic loss of human innocent life. And I personally, partly because of that, was not in favor of this invasion, but I also understood why it was taking place. The Israeli people overwhelmingly wanted Hamas eliminated taken out by the root. And in this war, a battle in Rafa was inevitable. So where do we go from here? Well, right now there is active and productive. I know people would say no, it's not productive, but it is negotiation taking place to establish a temporary. And yeah, it will likely be temporary ceasefire. It's a ceasefire that everyone needs Palestinians need aid. Israel needs some hostages return. They should have all of them return. And yeah, Hamas is planning on what to do next. It needs time for that planning. And my guess, and I think it's a good guess, is that there will be a ceasefire because all parties need it. And then likely there will be a battle in Rafa. Six weeks time will allow many Palestinians to leave Rafa and Hamas will lose that battle. I hope quickly. And after that, there will be more negotiations. And I don't know what will happen as a result of those, but I do know that there are major parties working for peace in the region. Saudis, United States, they're going to be squeezing both Israel and Palestine. I hope for the good of all people in their region that they succeed.

Content: The tiny glimmer of hope that Palestinians and Israelis would engage in a meaningful peace process was snuffed out between August 19th and the 21st 2003. A ceasefire had been agreed to in July, and while almost immediately and continually broke in these comparatively minor incidents were kind of being overlooked as the peace process splattered along. This all changed with the suicide bombing of a bus full of Israeli children in Jerusalem on the 19th, both Hamas and Islamic Jihad claimed responsibility, and so Israel attempted to assassinate their leadership and those responsible, killing and wounding bystanders in the process. These factions of Palestinian hardliners, who were never committed anyway, soon officially ended their participation in the ceasefire and declared themselves enemies of the peace plan. This in turn forced the recently appointed prime minister Mahmoud Abbas into the politically awkward position of cracking down on his fellow Palestinians in order to maintain his part of the peace deal. Still, he tried, but when Nasser Arafat refused to give him the resources needed to do this, Abbas, the only person Israel was willing to deal with resigned, and the conflict would continue to escalate until 2005.

Content: There was a panel discussion in New York Times the other day led by Emily Baselon, an excellent journalist, about why peace has been so impossible in the Middle East, and the panel consisted of Palestinians, Israelis, and neutral observers, and I encourage you to read it. And if you read that panel discussion, I'm sure you'll be like me, you'll come with your biases and find things you agree with and things you go, how could they say that? That's what makes that panel discussion so good. Am I bias? Everyone knows is Israel, right? That's where most of my family lives. But I do want peace. I want this horrific fighting to stop this month's fighting and fighting forever. And reading that panel discussion I was left with the impression that peace will come between Israel and Palestine only when both sides are weak and exhausted. And you may think I am delusional, but we are getting to the point where both sides are weak and completely exhausted. Israel is in fact weaker now than any time in my lifetime. It is weaker and less secure than it has been since 1948. Hundreds of thousands of Israelis have had to leave their border towns because they're no longer safe. That's never happened before. And today's existential enemy for Israel, and it is existential, is not really Hamas or the Palestinians, it's Iran and all the Iranian proxies, including Hamas. Iran and its proxies want to annihilate Israel and they are strong. And this war between Israel and Hamas probably would have already spread further, if not for the help of the United States, which is strategically bombing Iranian proxy targets in Iraq and elsewhere. Israel can no longer do it alone. And when this war ends, Hamas will be gone from governance, but Hamas will still be present in Gaza and Iran will still be a potent force trying to annihilate Israel. When this war ends, Israel will be weak and exhausted. I'm not happy about that. That's just the way it is. And when this war ends, Palestine will be weak and exhausted. About one-third of its populace will be living in rubble. And thousands of innocent civilians, Israeli, Palestinian, will have died. And if it's true that peace is really only possible in this region when both sides are weak and exhausted, it will be the best opportunity for peace. I'm not saying it's going to happen, but it will be the best opportunity for peace in the Middle East in 20 years.

Content: So what do I think about what's happening at Rafa? I try to not talk actually that much about what's happening in the Middle East on social media because the level of a conversation on social media about the Middle East is almost always terrible and infantile, always side blaming. And I tend to like to be constructive, which is not what social media is usually about. So how can anyone be constructive about what's happening during this Israel Hamas war and what's going to happen in Rafa? The war is a huge human tragedy. Everyone knew beforehand that it would be a huge human tragedy and no, it is not genocide. It is a war in an urban area. Everyone knew that there would be tragic loss of human innocent life. And I personally, partly because of that, was not in favor of this invasion, but I also understood why it was taking place. The Israeli people overwhelmingly wanted Hamas eliminated taken out by the root. And in this war, a battle in Rafa was inevitable. So where do we go from here? Well, right now there is active and productive. I know people would say no, it's not productive, but it is negotiation taking place to establish a temporary. And yeah, it will likely be temporary ceasefire. It's a ceasefire that everyone needs Palestinians need aid. Israel needs some hostages return. They should have all of them return. And yeah, Hamas is planning on what to do next. It needs time for that planning. And my guess, and I think it's a good guess, is that there will be a ceasefire because all parties need it. And then likely there will be a battle in Rafa. Six weeks time will allow many Palestinians to leave Rafa and Hamas will lose that battle. I hope quickly. And after that, there will be more negotiations. And I don't know what will happen as a result of those, but I do know that there are major parties working for peace in the region. Saudis, United States, they're going to be squeezing both Israel and Palestine. I hope for the good of all people in their region that they succeed.

Content: The tiny glimmer of hope that Palestinians and Israelis would engage in a meaningful peace process was snuffed out between August 19th and the 21st 2003. A ceasefire had been agreed to in July, and while almost immediately and continually broke in these comparatively minor incidents were kind of being overlooked as the peace process splattered along. This all changed with the suicide bombing of a bus full of Israeli children in Jerusalem on the 19th, both Hamas and Islamic Jihad claimed responsibility, and so Israel attempted to assassinate their leadership and those responsible, killing and wounding bystanders in the process. These factions of Palestinian hardliners, who were never committed anyway, soon officially ended their participation in the ceasefire and declared themselves enemies of the peace plan. This in turn forced the recently appointed prime minister Mahmoud Abbas into the politically awkward position of cracking down on his fellow Palestinians in order to maintain his part of the peace deal. Still, he tried, but when Nasser Arafat refused to give him the resources needed to do this, Abbas, the only person Israel was willing to deal with resigned, and the conflict would continue to escalate until 2005.

Content: This is the view that Nohasein has been looking at for the past 20 years. Behind the wall are the trees she planted and can no longer reach. People in the world wake up agitated from a bad nightmare, but here we are awake and are agitated every single day. The Israeli separation barrier cuts through her family's land in Katanna village, New Jerusalem. I heard the diggers working and saw them uprooting the trees. It was a deep pain in my heart. They didn't care when I lost the trees that I carried on my shoulders and planted one by one. That gets later Israeli forces are back for more. In August they handed several families in Katanna new confiscation orders to expand the wall. They fear that Israel will use the war on Gaza to grab more lands. This is our land and we have the proof. They say you're close to the illegal Israeli settlement, but I was here before the wall. The courts and power are in their hands. My future is over. I fear now for my children and grandchildren's future. Israel started building the wall during the second Palestinian uprising known as the Intifada. Palestinians say Israel used security as an excuse to confiscate more land. The wall's length is more than double that of the 1967 borders, snaking into Palestinian territory, running as deep as 18 kilometers inside the occupied West Bank. The UN says it's almost complete and will take up around 10 percent of Palestinian lands. The international court of justice has ruled the wall is illegal. Roads like this one are all what's left for Palestinians who often have to take longer routes to reach their destinations. For Palestinians the wall is an extension of Israel's system of control. Out of a wider network of roads, settlements and checkpoints built to give Israelis the upper hand while making their lives unbearable by the day. Nida Ebrahim Al-Jazira the occupied West Bank.

The success rate of intercepting a missile is 90 percent, while Hamas fires 5,000 rockets in a 20-minute frenzy. Can the Iron Dome truly defend against such a relentless attack? An Iron Dome anti-air system consists of three key components. This is the Combat Command Center. There's also the Missile Launch Unit. The most critical part is this detection and tracking radar. The Missile Launch Unit can hold up to 20 missiles, deploying it near a city, is like putting a protective shield over the city. The Combat Command Center is responsible for intercepting incoming orders. Attacks are only initiated when rockets enter a designated range. This small interceptor missiles surprisingly can cover a range of 70 kilometers, even though it's only 2.8 meters tall and weighs only 90 kilograms. Now, pay close attention. Here's the key point. When multiple enemy missiles are fired at the target city, the Iron Dome Defense System activates. First, the radar can detect threats within a 100 kilometer radius. Then it transmits the data to the Combat Command System, which sends instructions to the Missile Launch Unit and tracks the trajectory of enemy missiles. Data is transmitted from the radar to the Combat Command Center. Once a target is detected within the protected area, interceptor missiles are rapidly launched and locked on to the target. When they get close enough, the front warhead detonates. Inside, it contains shrapnel that detonates enemy bombs. It's important to note that a single Hamas rocket costs only $80, while intercepting it with an Iron Dome Missile costs $50,000. That's a significant difference in interception costs.

Content: Six facts about the Iron Dome, high success rate. The Iron Dome has an impressive success rate of intercepting incoming threats. During its deployment, it has reportedly intercepted over 90% of the rockets it targeted. Rapid response. One of its remarkable features is its ability to detect and intercept incoming projectiles within seconds. This quick response time is crucial for protecting populated areas from rocket attacks. Mobile and flexible. The system is highly mobile, allowing it to be deployed quickly to different locations as needed. Its flexibility enables it to adapt to changing threat scenarios. Interception technology. The Iron Dome uses advanced radar systems to track incoming projectiles and determine their trajectory. When a threat is detected, it launches interceptor missiles to destroy the incoming rockets before they reach their targets. Cost-effective defense. Despite its advanced technology, the Iron Dome is often praised for its cost-effectiveness. Intercepting incoming rockets with the Iron Dome is generally less expensive than allowing them to hit their targets, which could result in significant damage and casualties. International interest. The success of the Iron Dome has garnered international interest with several countries expressing interest in acquiring similar defense systems.

Content: Whoever invented Israel's Iron Dome Air Defense System was a genius. It operates automatically around the clock in all weather conditions and works wonders in intercepting and destroying short-range rockets and artillery shells. The system uses advanced optical radar and algorithms to predict the trajectory of incoming projectiles. And in less than a second, it determines whether they pose a threat to densely populated areas. If it detects a threat, it launches an interceptor missile that destroys the incoming projectile in mid-air. For less advanced rockets and mortars, Iron Dome has an intercept success rate of about 75 to 90%. A standard Iron Nest artillery battery usually consists of three or four mobile launching units, each carrying 20 ready-to-fire interceptor missiles. The cost of each interceptor missile is worth about $50,000, while enemy-launched rockets are much cheaper and more plentiful. The high cost also limits the number of ready-to-launch missiles, making precise targeting and interception critical. With one Iron Dome battery protecting a medium-sized city area, the Iron Dome system struggles to achieve 100% interception for intense attacks of short-flight close-range rockets, as well as for cost considerations. Although it provides a sophisticated defense, any system has limitations. As a result, Israel has also developed a multi-layered air defense system to deal with a variety of threats. The Iron Dome air defense system is the innermost layer of Israel's air defense system, and in the middle layer of Israel's air defense system, interceptor systems such as the spear of David play a vital role. This layer is designed to intercept targets such as airplanes, helicopters, and cruise missiles. The outermost layer of the air defense system consists of the arrow-long-range ballistic missile interceptor system, which is used to intercept long-range ballistic missile threats in the upper atmosphere and in space. In addition to the land-based system, Israel deploys the Maritime Iron Dome system, which provides 360-degree coverage of the coastline, and intercepts missiles launched from the sea. So before Muslims faced Mecca and prayer for the first half of Islam, they actually faced towards Jerusalem in their prayer. But I'll also say this, that the sanctity of a human being, the sanctity of just one person is greater than the sanctity of any place of worship to us. So the sanctity of one individual in Gaza or one individual in Jerusalem is greater to us than the sanctity of a place of worship. But it was all certainly interconnected. That's a really powerful idea. The value of a human being is greater than even the al-Aksa Mosque. That's a foundational idea for Islam. The Prophet Muhammad, peace be upon him, says to the Qabba itself, that the value of a believer's dignity and honor is greater than the value of the structure itself. And so when I see a person in Gaza, a guest upon, when I see one wala dhahdua, when I see one child, that's greater to me than even al-Aksa. But al-Aksa is at the heart of who we are as well. And it's certainly at the heart of the Palestinian cause. It's a place of prophets and it's a place that should be treated prophetically.

Content: If it's okay, you've mentioned Al-Aksa Mosque a couple of times. I would love it if you can describe why it is such an important place, a holy place for Muslims in general, but also for this particular crisis that we have been speaking about today. So Muslims honor the history of all of the prophets. So all of the prophets that have walked in that place, all of the prophets that have worshiped in that place, all of that makes it sacred. So it's not separated from Muslims from post-Muhammad's Peace be upon him versus prior to Muhammad's Peace be upon him in terms of the sanctity of that place. So we honor it. And Masjid Al-Aksa in particular is the place where the Prophet Muhammad Peace be upon him leads the other prophets in prayer in the night of what's known as at Islam and Mourage, the night journey of the Prophet Peace be upon him, and then he ascends to the heavens and back. And it's also the first Kibla, which is the first place of direction of prayer for us. So before Muslims faced Mecca and prayer for the first half of Islam, they actually faced towards Jerusalem in their prayer. It was our direction of prayer and it remained a fundamental part of our faith, our fundamental holy sanctuary. There are three sanctuaries in Islam, Mecca, Medina, and Jerusalem. And Masjid Al-Aksa is precious to us. And so you can imagine then the pain of watching innocent Palestinian worshippers being stomped on by Israeli soldiers or skunk water being sprayed on people as they're trying to walk in or tear gasping, taking place in the nights of Ramadan in that place. The restrictions on people that live right next to it and that cannot pray in it due to the certain classification of Palestinian that they've been given or the age, right? Because generally speaking, if you're younger, you're not allowed to go to Mecca, even if you live within the occupied territories. So it's tough to watch such a sacred place with such an ugly occupation. But I'll also say this, that the sanctity of a human being, the sanctity of just one person is greater than the sanctity of any place of worship to us. So the sanctity of one individual in Gaza or one individual in Jerusalem is greater to us than the sanctity of a place of worship. But it was all certainly interconnected. That's a really powerful idea. The value of a human being is greater than even the al-Aksa Mosque. That's a foundational idea for Islam. The Prophet Muhammad, peace be upon him, says to the Qabba itself, that the value of a believer's dignity and honor is greater than the value of the structure itself. And so when I see a person in Gaza, a guest upon, when I see one wala dhahdua, when I see one child, that's greater to me than even al-Aksa. But al-Aksa is at the heart of who we are as well. And it's certainly at the heart of the Palestinian cause. It's a place of prophets and it's a place that should be treated prophetically.

video_description: Replying to @rafina_rithsaqisya7980 Apakah yang dilakukan oleh Ariel Sharon?  #alymedia  #arielsharon  #fyp
Content: Nenek, dia lakukan oleh Errol Shiron, mari kita rungkai, pada 6,5,3 teraja di depok campungan kibia, dekat ramalah, mengurubankan 60 orang awam pelestin daram serangat tenter yang dipimpin olehnya, berang 6 hari pada 1567, jadi episod terkenal, dia manusia ron memimpin pasukan periata kembali selanjutnya, barang pas terbimbarat dan gaza, serta wilayah timu batu maklis, dan bukite golan, 6 tahun berikutnya, semasa perang yang kipur 15,7,3, liar dipanggil semula untuk memimpin pasukan merentah serusan seseorang. Dalam dunia politik, sebagai mentrib tanyang, Shiron memukir petempanta yangudi di depop bimbarat, semetara sebagai mentrib tahanan, boleh otelibat dalam peceruhuhan rubenan, termasuk pengapungan tadaap ibu perjabat pertuahan pembebasan pelestin PLO di Berut, dan pembantayan di campur yang sabar dan syatila pada tahun 1982. Keriannya teling 3,3 terakhir di Budara di sabar dan syatila, menyebabkan siasa taras mingguh menungguin beliau, butang kunja warstiar di dalam suhu. Shiron mencetuskan kemarhan dunia Islam dengan lawat tangkotroversinya kemahadat al-Asa pada 28 september 2000, yang memicu intifada kedua. Peri tahun 2001, Shiron meminvin penempengan ibu perjabat PLO di Ramalah, dan hanya membenarkan jasa arafat, yang itu berkasempir di perestin, keluar untuk rawatan, dan meninggal dunia tak lama kemudian. Desheran tekenal dengan rasa permisahan dengan pelestin, dan masuk pemina antimbo pemisah di depop bimbarat pada tahun 2002, mungkin ini sebab pahiran hidupnya menjadi seperti apa yang saya ketekan pada VTT sebelum ini. Terima kasih kerana menonton.

When he was in the Israeli defense force, Shiron let a raid which took the lives of at least 60 Palestinians civilians by dynamiting their homes after forgetting to check whether the homes were occupied. You know, people forget to check stuff all the time. For instance, before giving him power, somebody forgot to check whether Shiron was a decent human being. Shiron's raid, now known as the Kibbya Massacre, produced such a strong international backlash that Israel's Prime Minister, David Ben-Gurion, officially claimed that the soldiers involved were vigilantes and not the IDF. To put that in perspective, that means that it was worse than some of the things that Israel will say were the IDF. Shiron was born a royal shinerman. That doesn't sound right to me. I don't think Shiron ever took responsibility for anything. Shiron refused to resign after the commission's findings and was eventually allowed to stay in the Israeli cabinet as a minister without portfolio. For those of you unfamiliar with parliamentary governments, a minister without portfolio is pretty much the same, but they're only in charge of symbolic evil. Shiron was a complicated figure, and I do wanna make it clear that there's certain things he did that I approve of. For instance, I'm a big fan of the eight years when he didn't harm any civilians because he was in a vegetative state. All right, let me know who else I should roast. video_description: Replying to @rafina_rithsaqisya7980 Apakah yang dilakukan oleh Ariel Sharon?  #alymedia  #arielsharon  #fyp
Content: Nenek, dia lakukan oleh Errol Shiron, mari kita rungkai, pada 6,5,3 teraja di depok campungan kibia, dekat ramalah, mengurubankan 60 orang awam pelestin daram serangat tenter yang dipimpin olehnya, berang 6 hari pada 1567, jadi episod terkenal, dia manusia ron memimpin pasukan periata kembali selanjutnya, barang pas terbimbarat dan gaza, serta wilayah timu batu maklis, dan bukite golan, 6 tahun berikutnya, semasa perang yang kipur 15,7,3, liar dipanggil semula untuk memimpin pasukan merentah serusan seseorang. Dalam dunia politik, sebagai mentrib tanyang, Shiron memukir petempanta yangudi di depop bimbarat, semetara sebagai mentrib tahanan, boleh otelibat dalam peceruhuhan rubenan, termasuk pengapungan tadaap ibu perjabat pertuahan pembebasan pelestin PLO di Berut, dan pembantayan di campur yang sabar dan syatila pada tahun 1982. Keriannya teling 3,3 terakhir di Budara di sabar dan syatila, menyebabkan siasa taras mingguh menungguin beliau, butang kunja warstiar di dalam suhu. Shiron mencetuskan kemarhan dunia Islam dengan lawat tangkotroversinya kemahadat al-Asa pada 28 september 2000, yang memicu intifada kedua. Peri tahun 2001, Shiron meminvin penempengan ibu perjabat PLO di Ramalah, dan hanya membenarkan jasa arafat, yang itu berkasempir di perestin, keluar untuk rawatan, dan meninggal dunia tak lama kemudian. Desheran tekenal dengan rasa permisahan dengan pelestin, dan masuk pemina antimbo pemisah di depop bimbarat pada tahun 2002, mungkin ini sebab pahiran hidupnya menjadi seperti apa yang saya ketekan pada VTT sebelum ini. Terima kasih kerana menonton.

Content: Hi, I'm Noah and I wrote historical figures. Today I'll be roasting Israeli Prime Minister, General, and Crumpled Polar Bear, Arale Shiro. When he was in the Israeli defense force, Shiron let a raid which took the lives of at least 60 Palestinians civilians by dynamiting their homes after forgetting to check whether the homes were occupied. You know, people forget to check stuff all the time. For instance, before giving him power, somebody forgot to check whether Shiron was a decent human being. Shiron's raid, now known as the Kibbya Massacre, produced such a strong international backlash that Israel's Prime Minister, David Ben-Gurion, officially claimed that the soldiers involved were vigilantes and not the IDF. To put that in perspective, that means that it was worse than some of the things that Israel will say were the IDF. Shiron was born a royal shinerman. It didn't change his name until Ben-Gurion suggested the more Hebrew sounding Shiron. There's a lot of great reasons change your name, but this isn't one. My family changed their name to avoid anti-Semitism. Shiron changed his so criticism sounded like anti-Semitism. Later, when Shiron was defense minister, an Israeli commission ruled that the Sabra and Shatila massacre, which killed hundreds to thousands of civilians in Beirut was Shiron's personal responsibility. That doesn't sound right to me. I don't think Shiron ever took responsibility for anything. Shiron refused to resign after the commission's findings and was eventually allowed to stay in the Israeli cabinet as a minister without portfolio. For those of you unfamiliar with parliamentary governments, a minister without portfolio is pretty much the same, but they're only in charge of symbolic evil. Shiron was a complicated figure, and I do wanna make it clear that there's certain things he did that I approve of. For instance, I'm a big fan of the eight years when he didn't harm any civilians because he was in a vegetative state. All right, let me know who else I should roast. And join me next time for part two of my roast of Israeli prime minister, General, and a guy who looks like he just heard that this sheep is living in a home that a settler wants, Arale Shiron.
