Content: Hi, I'm Noah and I roast historical figures. Today is part two of my roast of Israeli Prime Minister, general, and the guy who looks like the patriarch in a midi-set Tennessee Williams play, Ariel Shorou. During the 1956 Sinai campaign, troops under Shorouan's command summarily executed 49 Egyptians, civilians that they had taken prisoner because, as one soldier put it, they were a burden. That's so stupid and evil. You know what's objectively less of a burden than keeping prisoners, not taking the prisoner in the first place? Although Shorouan was in charge of that unit, it's never been proven that he ordered those executions, although it's definitely true that he didn't punish the soldiers who carried them out. Makes me think of that quote, the only thing necessary for evil to triumph is for good men to do nothing. It turns out, it works if bad men do nothing too. Out of the 1977 elections, Shorouan pitched himself as a party leader to right, center, and left-wing parties, but was rejected by all three, forcing him to found his own. I've heard that Shorouan united Israel. I didn't realize that he united Israel against him. As Defense Minister in the 80s, Shorouan maintained Israel's close relationship with apartheid era South Africa, selling them weapons and cooperating militarily despite a UN arms embargo against them. Syniks will say that Shorouan compromises principles for the beneficial alliance, but I say what principles? Shorouan is remembered for ending Israeli settlements in Gaza in 2005, despite settlements and palestinian territories actually growing over his time as Prime Minister. That seems unfair. That'd be like if I was remembered for all the tasteless jokes I didn't make instead of the very rude one I made at the end of the last video on Shorouan. According to a close Shorouan aide, his disengagement from Gaza was designed to cut off Gaza and freeze the political peace process. They say when all you have is a hammer, everything looks like a nail, but when all you have is Shorouan's brain, everything looks like a way to continue an occupation. All right, let me know who else I should roast and join me next time when I'll be roasting Mayor of Chicago and a guy who looks like he was born to be in his Corsese movie for five minutes, Richard J. Daily.

Content: Inilah Azap untuk pembunuh rakyat palestin, Aril Sharon terkenal sebagai pemimpin Israel yang bertindak ganas dan kejam. Namun nasibnya berakhir dengan ragi skarna di serang stroke, Aril Koma selama 8 tahun dan mati reput di hospital pada usia 85 tahun. Semasa Aril Koma, organ di dalam badannya rusak dan menjadi busuk sehingga tidak dapat berfungsi. Sebelum Aril Sharon Jatukoma, pembandu pribadi-badi nya memberi tahu Aril sering di ganggu oleh satu mimpi yang sama. Di dalam mimpi itu Aril Sharon telah di siksa, di rantai tangan dan kakinya, kemudian diharap sekeliling bandar gaza dan dimasukkan ke dalam habis, mimpi itu mengganggu Sharon setiap malam hingga diajat Koma, segala peralatan canggin yang dipasang di badannya selama 8 tahun tidak mampu menelamakan hari. Sabdar Rasulullah Solalahu Alaihi Wasalam, wahai Tuhan Kuh, barang siapa yang dilantik memberuskan urusan humatku ini lalu dia menyusakan urusan humatku. Content: The Golden Heights have been disputed by Israel and Syria for more than half a century, but is certainly Israel's lesser-covered territorial view. Israel captured most of the 1,800 square kilometer plateau from Syria during the 6th day war in 1967 with Syria trying and failing to retake it in 1973. An armistice was signed in 1974 and a UN observer force has been stationed along the frontier ever since. With things remaining relatively quiet, with fertile soil and crucial water sources, the Golden is also important to Israel as a useful buffer zone with Syria. Israel unilaterally annexed the Golden in 1981, but the international community still views it as occupied Syrian territory, while only the US recognizes it as Israeli, a move made by Donald Trump in 2019. The Golden is home to some 20,000 Syrians, mostly Drew's Arabs, and more than 20,000 Israeli settlers living in settlements considered illegal under international law, with Israel planning to double the Israeli population by 2027.

Content: On behalf of the current EU members of the Security Council, France, Germany, Poland, the UK and my own country, Belgium, we would like to make a brief statement on the occupied Golan Heights. In the context of the US presidential proclamation, to yesterday, stating that the United States recognizes that the Golan Heights are part of the state of Israel. Our position on the status of the Golan Heights is well known, and we would like to make it clear that this position has not changed. In line with international law and relevant security council resolutions, not only resolution 242 and 497, we do not recognize Israel's sovereignty over the territories occupied by Israel since June 1967. Including the Golan Heights, and we do not consider them to be part of the territory of the state of Israel. An accession of territory by force is prohibited under international law. Any declaration of a unilateral border change goes against the foundation of the rules-based international order and the UN charter. We raise our stronger concerns about the broader consequences of recognizing illegal annexation.

Content: The Golden Heights have been disputed by Israel and Syria for more than half a century, but is certainly Israel's lesser-covered territorial view. Israel captured most of the 1,800 square kilometer plateau from Syria during the 6th day war in 1967 with Syria trying and failing to retake it in 1973. An armistice was signed in 1974 and a UN observer force has been stationed along the frontier ever since. With things remaining relatively quiet, with fertile soil and crucial water sources, the Golden is also important to Israel as a useful buffer zone with Syria. Israel unilaterally annexed the Golden in 1981, but the international community still views it as occupied Syrian territory, while only the US recognizes it as Israeli, a move made by Donald Trump in 2019. The Golden is home to some 20,000 Syrians, mostly Drew's Arabs, and more than 20,000 Israeli settlers living in settlements considered illegal under international law, with Israel planning to double the Israeli population by 2027.

Content: This video is an introduction to a series of videos I'll be making going over the Goldstone report. And if you're not familiar with what the Goldstone report is, it was a report that was published in 2009 that investigated all violations of international human rights law and international humanitarian law that might have been committed at any time in the context of the military operations that were conducted in Gaza. The president of the Human Rights Council at the time appointed Justice Richard Goldstone to head the mission. Goldstone was a former judge of the Constitutional Court of South Africa and former prosecutor of the International Criminal Tribunals for former Yugoslavia and Rwanda. The next three members were Professor Christine Chinken, Professor of International Law at the London School of Economics and Political Science, who was a member of the high-level fact-finding mission to bait Hanun, one of the most northern towns in the Gaza Strip and is currently destroyed beyond recognition. Next, Ms. Hina Jalani, advocate of the Supreme Court of Pakistan and former special representative of the Secretary-General on the Situation of Human Rights Defenders, who was a member of the International Commission of Inquiry on Darfur. And lastly, Colonel Desmond Travers, a former officer in Ireland's Defense Forces and member of the Board of Directors of the Institute for International Criminal Investigations. Quoting the report, the mission interpreted the mandate as requiring it to place the civilian population of the region at the center of its concern regarding the violations of international law. The mission convened for the first time in Geneva between May 4th and 8th, 2009, additionally the mission met in Geneva on May 20th and on July 4th and 5th and between the 1st and 4th of August of 2009. The mission conducted three field visits, two to the Gaza Strip between May 30th and June 6th and between June 25th and July 1st of 2009, and one visit to Aiman, July 2nd and 3rd of 2009. Several staff of the mission secretary were deployed in Gaza from May 22nd to July 4th of 2009 to conduct field investigations. Notes for Bales, a note for Bales is a diplomatic communication from one government to another delivered through each other's diplomatic representatives. Also, I'm very aware of that's a French word, so it literally means verbal note, but this is, you know, fancy way to say it and how they document it within government documents. They were sent to all member states of the United Nations and United Nations organs and bodies on May 7th, 2009 and on June 8th of 2009. The mission issued a call for submissions inviting all interested persons and organizations to submit relevant information and documentation to assist in the implementation of its mandate. Public hearings were held in Gaza June 28th and 29th and in Geneva and July 6th and 7th of 2009. The mission repeatedly sought to obtain the operation of the government of Israel after numerous attempts had failed. The mission sought and obtained the assistance of the government of Egypt to enable it to enter the Gaza Strip to the Rafa Crossing. The mission conducted 188 individual interviews. It reviewed more than 300 reports, submissions and other documentation either research of its own motion, received a reply to its call for submissions and verbal note or provided during meetings or otherwise, amounting to more than 10,000 pages, over 30 videos and 1,200 photographs.

Content: Hello again everybody. I wanted to make another video today. This one is going to be on the UNRWA or the United Nations Relief and Works Agency. This agency was established by the United Nations in 1949 after the creation of the State of Israel. It's intended purpose is and was to help Palestinians that have been displaced due to the actions of the State of Israel. It's sort of hard to quantify all of the things that the UNRWA does. They have around 30,000 staff members and they provide education, health services, human resources like food and water. They run refugee camps. They just provide a lot of relief for Palestinians that live both in the West Bank and Gaza and in the diaspora. You can see here off of the UNRWA website that 3 million people regularly use the health services that are provided by the UNRWA. The reason that I'm making this video is that shortly after the ICJ issued its preliminary decision saying that the charge of genocide against Israel was quote unquote plausible. The State of Israel seemed to seek some retribution and the retribution that they sought was classifying the UNRWA as a terrorist organization. They said that 7 of the UNRWA employees were participants in the October 7th attacks. I think it's extremely important to point out that Israel provided literally zero documentation, zero evidence to back up these claims that they were making against the UNRWA. As a result of these allegations, countries like the US, the UK, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Finland, Switzerland, Canada and Australia, all simultaneously paused or pulled their funding for the UNRWA. This organization relies heavily on these voluntary donations by these countries and the UNRWA has come out and said they are not sure if they're going to be able to continue providing services through the end of this year. I know that the US and the UK alone provide around $600 million a year in funding. So by them cutting funding, this is a gigantic financial hit to the organization. Given what's going on and continues to go on in both Gaza and the West Bank, this organization's services are needed now perhaps more than ever. Fortunately, if you go to UNRWA.org, you can access their website. You can learn more about the organization, what services they provide, where they operate, etc. And you can also donate through this website. So I encourage every single one of you to go take a look at their website. If you can, please consider donating to the organization because they are in dire need of these funds in order to keep these services operational and going. If you are not in a position to donate, that's totally fine. I understand. If you could like, share and comment on this video just to push the message app as far as possible. And I also encourage you to do your own research. Make your own videos. Keep the conversation going so hopefully we can assist in keeping this vital organization intact and providing services to those who need it. I thank you all so much for watching and listening. Free Palestine.

video_description: The exposure of UNRWA (United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East) has shed light on significant challenges within the organization. UNRWA, tasked with providing essential services to Palestinian refugees, has faced scrutiny over allegations of mismanagement, corruption, and politicization of aid. Revelations regarding financial misappropriation, misconduct among staff, and perpetuation of dependency cycles have raised concerns about the effectiveness and integrity of UNRWA's operations. The exposure has prompted calls for accountability, transparency, and structural reforms to ensure that humanitarian assistance reaches those most in need while upholding the principles of neutrality and impartiality. As efforts to address these issues continue, there is a pressing need to prioritize the well-being and rights of Palestinian refugees, ensuring that they receive the support and services they require for dignified living conditions and sustainable futures.

Content: As Palestinian children and Gaza literally starved to death in the spectra of a man-made famine looms, Israel continues its war against the United Nations' relief and works agency for Palestine refugees in the Near East, or UNRWA, which crucially provides direct services, food, education, healthcare to millions of Palestinians, especially in Gaza. So time for another debunked, seven Israeli myths about UNRWA. Myth number one, UNRWA is only for Palestinians. What about Jewish refugees? Well, actually UNRWA was established in 1949 by the UN General Assembly, and Israel was one of the countries that voted in favor of it. In fact, in the wake of what Israel calls its war of independence and what Palestinians call the NACPA, and for the first two full years of its existence, UNRWA also provided relief to Jewish refugees from that conflict up until 1952, when the Israelis decided they would take over that mission. And in 1967, it was the Israelis who occupied the West Bank and Gaza, and then insisted UNRWA stick around to look after the local Palestinian population. Myth number two, you don't need UNRWA. You could just have the UNHCR, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, which takes care of all the other refugees in the world. It could take care of Palestinian refugees too. Nope, not true. UNRWA was set up in 1949, and its mandate to deal specifically with 1948 refugees from Palestine comes from the UN General Assembly. The UNHCR was set up a year later in 1950, and its mandate comes from the refugee convention, which explicitly said it didn't apply to refugees already receiving assistance from other UN agencies. Also, the UNHCR doesn't do direct services the way UNRWA does. Myth number three, UNRWA, unlike other refugee agencies, allows the descendants of Palestinian refugees to claim refugee status too, and thereby inflates and perpetuates the refugee problem. Sorry what? And the international law, the children of refugees are also refugees. That's not a Palestinian thing, that's an Afghan thing, that's a Somali thing, that's a Tibetan thing. In fact, UNRWA, unlike the UNHCR, says that only fathers, not mothers, can transfer refugee status to their descendants. thereby excluding a significant amount of Palestinians across the world who would otherwise be able to claim refugee status. Myth number four, UNRWA textbooks teach anti-Semitic hate to Palestinian kids. Not true. In fact, a Trump State Department report found that 97% of those textbooks contain no anti-Semitic or even anti-Israel bias. 3% is still bad, I know, but it's a tiny minority. Myth number five, UNRWA is in cooots with Hamas in Gaza. Actually, Hamas doesn't really like UNRWA, never has. Here's a story from 10 years ago about Hamas being peeved at UNRWA because it was too western, not in line with conservative Islamic values and a bit of a competitor with Hamas in terms of providing social services to Gaza's population. In fact, Hamas has been accused of threatening and even trying to assassinate UNRWA staff. Myth number six, 12 UNRWA employees were involved in the October 7th, Hamas attacks on Israel. First off, even if there were 12 UNRWA employees who participated in that barbarism, that's 12 out of 13,000 UNRWA employees in Gaza, less than 0.01% of the total, and yet the US agreed to halt vital humanitarian aid for millions of Palestinians via UNRWA because of that alleged 0.01%. Second, we don't even know if 12 employees were involved. Israel is often no hard evidence. Despite Secretary Blinken claiming Israel's claims on this were highly credible, an internal US intelligence report says it has low confidence that UNRWA staffers were part of the attack and says Israel has not shared the raw intelligence behind its assessments. And last week, UNRWA said in an internal report that some of their employees were tortured by the Israelis into making false claims about UNRWA staff as taking part on October 7th. But that report from UNRWA hasn't had as much coverage as the initial Israeli claims about UNRWA. You'll be shocked to hear. And finally, Myth number seven, there is no Israeli plan to deliberately destroy UNRWA. That's just a Palestinian conspiracy theory. Oh really, a Palestinian conspiracy theory, you say. Meet Noga Arbal, a former Israeli foreign ministry official. Here she is testifying in front of the Israeli parliament in January. In fact, this week we learn that Israeli military is bent on dismantling on eliminating UNRWA. So forget the lies, the myth, the propaganda. This is an Israeli war on UNRWA and by extension on the starving people of Gaza. Why on earth is the United States joining in?

video_description: The exposure of UNRWA (United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East) has shed light on significant challenges within the organization. UNRWA, tasked with providing essential services to Palestinian refugees, has faced scrutiny over allegations of mismanagement, corruption, and politicization of aid. Revelations regarding financial misappropriation, misconduct among staff, and perpetuation of dependency cycles have raised concerns about the effectiveness and integrity of UNRWA's operations. The exposure has prompted calls for accountability, transparency, and structural reforms to ensure that humanitarian assistance reaches those most in need while upholding the principles of neutrality and impartiality. As efforts to address these issues continue, there is a pressing need to prioritize the well-being and rights of Palestinian refugees, ensuring that they receive the support and services they require for dignified living conditions and sustainable futures.

Content: As Palestinian children and Gaza literally starved to death in the spectra of a man-made famine looms, Israel continues its war against the United Nations' relief and works agency for Palestine refugees in the Near East, or UNRWA, which crucially provides direct services, food, education, healthcare to millions of Palestinians, especially in Gaza. So time for another debunked, seven Israeli myths about UNRWA. Myth number one, UNRWA is only for Palestinians. What about Jewish refugees? Well, actually UNRWA was established in 1949 by the UN General Assembly, and Israel was one of the countries that voted in favor of it. In fact, in the wake of what Israel calls its war of independence and what Palestinians call the NACPA, and for the first two full years of its existence, UNRWA also provided relief to Jewish refugees from that conflict up until 1952, when the Israelis decided they would take over that mission. And in 1967, it was the Israelis who occupied the West Bank and Gaza, and then insisted UNRWA stick around to look after the local Palestinian population. Myth number two, you don't need UNRWA. You could just have the UNHCR, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, which takes care of all the other refugees in the world. It could take care of Palestinian refugees too. Nope, not true. UNRWA was set up in 1949, and its mandate to deal specifically with 1948 refugees from Palestine comes from the UN General Assembly. The UNHCR was set up a year later in 1950, and its mandate comes from the refugee convention, which explicitly said it didn't apply to refugees already receiving assistance from other UN agencies. Also, the UNHCR doesn't do direct services the way UNRWA does. Myth number three, UNRWA, unlike other refugee agencies, allows the descendants of Palestinian refugees to claim refugee status too, and thereby inflates and perpetuates the refugee problem. Sorry what? And the international law, the children of refugees are also refugees. That's not a Palestinian thing, that's an Afghan thing, that's a Somali thing, that's a Tibetan thing. In fact, UNRWA, unlike the UNHCR, says that only fathers, not mothers, can transfer refugee status to their descendants. thereby excluding a significant amount of Palestinians across the world who would otherwise be able to claim refugee status. Myth number four, UNRWA textbooks teach anti-Semitic hate to Palestinian kids. Not true. In fact, a Trump State Department report found that 97% of those textbooks contain no anti-Semitic or even anti-Israel bias. 3% is still bad, I know, but it's a tiny minority. Myth number five, UNRWA is in cooots with Hamas in Gaza. Actually, Hamas doesn't really like UNRWA, never has. Here's a story from 10 years ago about Hamas being peeved at UNRWA because it was too western, not in line with conservative Islamic values and a bit of a competitor with Hamas in terms of providing social services to Gaza's population. In fact, Hamas has been accused of threatening and even trying to assassinate UNRWA staff. Myth number six, 12 UNRWA employees were involved in the October 7th, Hamas attacks on Israel. First off, even if there were 12 UNRWA employees who participated in that barbarism, that's 12 out of 13,000 UNRWA employees in Gaza, less than 0.01% of the total, and yet the US agreed to halt vital humanitarian aid for millions of Palestinians via UNRWA because of that alleged 0.01%. Second, we don't even know if 12 employees were involved. Israel is often no hard evidence. Despite Secretary Blinken claiming Israel's claims on this were highly credible, an internal US intelligence report says it has low confidence that UNRWA staffers were part of the attack and says Israel has not shared the raw intelligence behind its assessments. And last week, UNRWA said in an internal report that some of their employees were tortured by the Israelis into making false claims about UNRWA staff as taking part on October 7th. But that report from UNRWA hasn't had as much coverage as the initial Israeli claims about UNRWA. You'll be shocked to hear. And finally, Myth number seven, there is no Israeli plan to deliberately destroy UNRWA. That's just a Palestinian conspiracy theory. Oh really, a Palestinian conspiracy theory, you say. Meet Noga Arbal, a former Israeli foreign ministry official. Here she is testifying in front of the Israeli parliament in January. In fact, this week we learn that Israeli military is bent on dismantling on eliminating UNRWA. So forget the lies, the myth, the propaganda. This is an Israeli war on UNRWA and by extension on the starving people of Gaza. Why on earth is the United States joining in?

Content: As Palestinian children and Gaza literally starved to death in the spectra of a man-made famine looms, Israel continues its war against the United Nations' relief and works agency for Palestine refugees in the Near East, or UNRWA, which crucially provides direct services, food, education, healthcare to millions of Palestinians, especially in Gaza. So time for another debunked, seven Israeli myths about UNRWA. Myth number one, UNRWA is only for Palestinians. What about Jewish refugees? Well, actually UNRWA was established in 1949 by the UN General Assembly, and Israel was one of the countries that voted in favor of it. In fact, in the wake of what Israel calls its war of independence and what Palestinians call the NACPA, and for the first two full years of its existence, UNRWA also provided relief to Jewish refugees from that conflict up until 1952, when the Israelis decided they would take over that mission. And in 1967, it was the Israelis who occupied the West Bank and Gaza, and then insisted UNRWA stick around to look after the local Palestinian population. Myth number two, you don't need UNRWA. You could just have the UNHCR, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, which takes care of all the other refugees in the world. It could take care of Palestinian refugees too. Nope, not true. UNRWA was set up in 1949, and its mandate to deal specifically with 1948 refugees from Palestine comes from the UN General Assembly. The UNHCR was set up a year later in 1950, and its mandate comes from the refugee convention, which explicitly said it didn't apply to refugees already receiving assistance from other UN agencies. Also, the UNHCR doesn't do direct services the way UNRWA does. Myth number three, UNRWA, unlike other refugee agencies, allows the descendants of Palestinian refugees to claim refugee status too, and thereby inflates and perpetuates the refugee problem. Sorry what? And the international law, the children of refugees are also refugees. That's not a Palestinian thing, that's an Afghan thing, that's a Somali thing, that's a Tibetan thing. In fact, UNRWA, unlike the UNHCR, says that only fathers, not mothers, can transfer refugee status to their descendants. thereby excluding a significant amount of Palestinians across the world who would otherwise be able to claim refugee status. Myth number four, UNRWA textbooks teach anti-Semitic hate to Palestinian kids. Not true. In fact, a Trump State Department report found that 97% of those textbooks contain no anti-Semitic or even anti-Israel bias. 3% is still bad, I know, but it's a tiny minority. Myth number five, UNRWA is in cooots with Hamas in Gaza. Actually, Hamas doesn't really like UNRWA, never has. Here's a story from 10 years ago about Hamas being peeved at UNRWA because it was too western, not in line with conservative Islamic values and a bit of a competitor with Hamas in terms of providing social services to Gaza's population. In fact, Hamas has been accused of threatening and even trying to assassinate UNRWA staff. Myth number six, 12 UNRWA employees were involved in the October 7th, Hamas attacks on Israel. First off, even if there were 12 UNRWA employees who participated in that barbarism, that's 12 out of 13,000 UNRWA employees in Gaza, less than 0.01% of the total, and yet the US agreed to halt vital humanitarian aid for millions of Palestinians via UNRWA because of that alleged 0.01%. Second, we don't even know if 12 employees were involved. Israel is often no hard evidence. Despite Secretary Blinken claiming Israel's claims on this were highly credible, an internal US intelligence report says it has low confidence that UNRWA staffers were part of the attack and says Israel has not shared the raw intelligence behind its assessments. And last week, UNRWA said in an internal report that some of their employees were tortured by the Israelis into making false claims about UNRWA staff as taking part on October 7th. But that report from UNRWA hasn't had as much coverage as the initial Israeli claims about UNRWA. You'll be shocked to hear. And finally, Myth number seven, there is no Israeli plan to deliberately destroy UNRWA. That's just a Palestinian conspiracy theory. Oh really, a Palestinian conspiracy theory, you say. Meet Noga Arbal, a former Israeli foreign ministry official. Here she is testifying in front of the Israeli parliament in January. In fact, this week we learn that Israeli military is bent on dismantling on eliminating UNRWA. So forget the lies, the myth, the propaganda. This is an Israeli war on UNRWA and by extension on the starving people of Gaza. Why on earth is the United States joining in?

Content: If you thought that we were done discussing Palestine and Israel, we weren't. Let's talk about the Oslo Accords. Israel and the PLO, Palestinian Liberation Organization, signed the Oslo Accords in 1993. It marked the first time Israel and the PLO formally recognized each other. The Accords were signed in Oslo, Norway, and aimed to set up the Palestine Authority as an interim government that was supposed to transform into a permanent one and concluded by the end of 1999. Israel and Palestine were given five years to come up with an agreement for the two-state solution. Yasin Haddad Fad was allowed to return from exile to the Palestinian territories. 28 years later, there is still no solution and the West Bank is still occupied illegally by Israel.

Content: She's a rapper, record producer, and singer known for her eclectic music style, and she supports the Palestinian people. She's MIA. Born in London to Sri Lankan, Tamil parents, her upbringing was marked by displacement due to the Sri Lankan Civil War, which influenced her artistry. MIA gained fame through the internet in the early 2000s, and achieved critical acclaim with albums like Arular in 2005 and Kala in 2007. Despite being born in London, MIA spent her childhood in war-torn northern Sri Lanka. She has said that her father was a Tamil revolutionary who trained with the Palestine Liberation Organization. Throughout her career, MIA has expressed support for Palestine through her lyrics and public statements. Her music video for the song Sun Showers from her debut album was banned from MTV due to its references to the Palestine Liberation Organization. The music video includes the line, like PLO, I Don't Surrender. She again represents Palestine on the song Illy Girl from her 2010 album Maya. With the lyrics, I know Billie Jean, I know Bruce Springsteen, I also know Palestine. In October 2023, she put out a statement that said, The events unfolding in Palestine is very traumatic, a decade after what happened to Tamil people. An alleged that she's being denied a visa now because she spoke out against Israel, which she labeled as genocidal and called for a ceasefire. Content: Part two of the free Gaza movement, Flotilla incident in May of 2010 on the Black Aid of Gaza. My name is Suzanne Malner, I'm the Executive Director of Beirut Beyond, and I have spent 19 years working with Palestinian refugees. Now, for context, I would go back to Part one to get context on this, but we left off on May 30, 2010 with the Flotilla, six ships leaving Cyprus for Gaza. Let's go. On May 31, Israeli authorities contacted the ship and told them to redirect to Ashtad, and free Gaza movement communicated that they were going to Gaza. So, during the night of May 31, Flotilla did not comply with Israeli directives, so the Israeli military decided to activate helicopters approached and armed troops repelled down onto the ships. The biggest attack was on the Mavimarmara, one of the biggest ships. They attacked with tear gas, stun guns, and guns. Most of the passengers reacted non-violently. Some had white flags that was reported. But once it became clear that these armed men were going to board the ship, some reacted violently. During the assault, Israeli troops beat an open fire on primarily non-violent activists. Some activists use clubs and change to beat the commandos with. At the end of the brief and chaotic and bloody attack, you had dozens of activist injured and nine activists dead. At the end of the attack, Israeli forces towed the ships to Israeli shore and said that they agreed to deliver the humanitarian aid, as long as it did not violate their black aid on Gaza. But Hamas said that they wanted to break the black aid and not just receive goods, so they refused to accept the aid and Israel never delivered it. Now, interestingly enough, on June 17, Israel announced a relaxation of the black aid. Of course, all of the activists were placed in Israeli detention. They were released between June 1 and June 6. Now, of course, Israel's saved international severe criticism, the UN and the International Committee of the Red Cross, both released reports criticizing Israel's actions. And since the majority of the activists were Turkish, Israel's relationship with Turkey was severely fractured. If you didn't know now you do, please like and follow for more information on Palestinian refugees.

The biggest attack was on the Mavimarmara, one of the biggest ships. They attacked with tear gas, stun guns, and guns. Most of the passengers reacted non-violently. Some had white flags that was reported. But once it became clear that these armed men were going to board the ship, some reacted violently. During the assault, Israeli troops beat an open fire on primarily non-violent activists. Some activists use clubs and change to beat the commandos with. At the end of the brief and chaotic and bloody attack, you had dozens of activist injured and nine activists dead. At the end of the attack, Israeli forces towed the ships to Israeli shore and said that they agreed to deliver the humanitarian aid, as long as it did not violate their black aid on Gaza. But Hamas said that they wanted to break the black aid and not just receive goods, so they refused to accept the aid and Israel never delivered it. I‚Äôm so proud of your spirit my brother and a picture of my dad with his teamü§ç It started with two incidents represent turning points in Malaysian support for Palestine: the Mavi Marmara ‚ÄúFreedom Flotilla‚Äù incident, The first took place in 2010 and boosted public support in Malaysia in an unprecedented way. Malaysian activists were on board the Mavi Marmara, which was carrying humanitarian aid to the Gaza Strip when it was attacked in international waters by Israeli commandos. Nine Turkish citizens were killed during the assault ‚Äî one more died later of his wounds ‚Äî and Malaysia raged at the incident. Public support for Palestine has been high ever since.  One of the activists was my Dad,he was captured and hostile for 24 hours until luckily was released with no passport,belongings and traumatised by the shooting that occurred in front of his eyes. The heartbreaking incident certainly left an impact on everyone involved, so my father often reminded us to always support humanitarian efforts and uphold humanity. video_description: Israel : The Right of Returns #fyp #palestine #israel #freepalestineüáµüá∏‚ù§Ô∏è
Content: This whole issue of Israel and Palestine is covered in so much myth. And there's so much double standard when people talk about this issue. And I'll give you two examples. I don't know if you heard Bibin et Tha'Niau speech at the United Nations. I heard it not live, but after he actually delivered it. And he began it with probably the tomb of striking examples of a myth and double standard. And he began by talking about the right of return of the Jews to their ancient homeland. And of course the Jews that returned, so-called returned to their homeland, were not exactly the same Jews who were expelled from their homeland. Because these were expelled a couple of thousand years before that. These were not their descendants either because they- this has been a very long time. So these are people, the people that actually came back, so to speak, are people that claim some kind of a heritage, some kind of a connection or a relationship to the ancient Hebrews. And they claimed that they had the right to return to their homeland. This was what Zionism was about and this was accepted by the world. As the right, they had the right to return. Now if we talk about the right of return of what nation you'd expect that there would be, if we accept it as a principle, then you'd expect that we'd accept it in general across the board. Yet when people talk about the right of return of Palestinians to their homeland, suddenly a red line comes up and everybody says, no, we can't talk about the right of return of the Palestinians. This has to be taken off the table. This is not negotiable. The right of return of the Palestinians is not acceptable. What's interesting about that is that the right of return of the Palestinians, we're talking about, quite often, we talk about the actual people who had to leave their homes. And if they had already passed away, then we're talking about their direct descendants. People who still have the keys and the deeds to their homes, and quite often can go to the very spot where a village existed, where today there might be a highway, and we'll point out the mosque, and we'll point out the well, and we'll point out the door to their home. Yet they do not enjoy the right to return. So obviously this is a double standard of immense proportions. The other thing BB talked about right off as he started was about King David, who reigned some 3,000 years ago, and here we are today as his descendants. What's interesting is, besides the fact that there is no historical evidence that King David ever existed, outside the Bible, which of course is not a historical document. And Israeli archaeologists have all but turned up the entire country to find proof that he ever existed. Today, as we speak, an entire town and entire community is being kicked out of their homes and forced into exile through violence in order to prove the King David existed in a place called Silwan. It's a community of 50,000 people right outside the walls of the old city of Jerusalem. Yet the world sees nothing wrong with this. American money is poured into this project to build what is called the new city of David, an archaeological park, and a community of 50,000 Palestinians has to be terrorized in order to leave their homes are being destroyed in order to make this point. This fictional mythical connection between the ancient Kingdom of King David and today's Israel.

Content: Why is a key the most important position many Palestinian refugees own? The key is the most symbolic symbol to Palestinians and most specifically to Palestinian refugees, as it represents their right of return. At least 750,000 Palestinians were forced out of their homes during the ethnic cleansing of 1948, also known as the Nakhba. Zionist forces invaded historic Palestine and captured 78% of Palestinian land. Hundreds of Palestinian villages were destroyed and some 15,000 Palestinians were killed. Israel banned most Palestinian refugees from ever returning to their homes. Due to the creation of Israel taking place in such a short amount of time, we saw huge numbers of Palestinian's become refugees and they were forced to leave and flee their homes, leaving everything but behind. Except one thing, the key to their homes and they kept this key on the belief that one day they would return. There are about 6 million Palestinian refugees in the occupied West Bank, Gaza and neighbouring countries. Many still cling to the hope of returning home and the key represents that. You'll see a huge number of these Palestinian refugees still holding onto their keys of their homes from before 1948 and this become kind of this unspoken generational gift onto the next generation. But if that generation who's holding onto the key of their home at that time, if they are not physically able to live to see a decolonized Palestine and to go back to their home, they'll pass on to that key onto the next generation. Many older Palestinians still remember their lives and homes before the Nakhba took place and hope to return. I find it both heartbreaking and angering to see that we have to see yet another generation pass on these keys to their grandchildren, to their own children and it's not them themselves returning to Palestine. As a part of Qifle-Ti'at we say we want to see return within our lifetimes and we want to see our elders, not their grandchildren, not their great-great-grandchildren, but the our elders, the ones who personally had to flee from the Nakhba, we want to see them return in our lifetimes. For our founded Qifle-Ti'at in 2017 to mark 100 years of the Balfour Declaration, that's when the British government gave support for an adjouish homeland in Palestine. When we created this, we wanted a visible symbol for people to see that one of the key solutions to Palestine isn't this regurgitated, insincere rhetoric or two-state solution, but one of the key solutions in itself is our key is our right to pattern. The right to pattern lies at the heart of what should happen next when we talk about Palestine, which is decolonization, which is dismantling these really settler colonial projects. Key 48 has issued over 10,000 symbolic keys and 30 countries to raise awareness about Palestinian rights. The group has been supported by Bella Hadid and Roger Waters. And that's the most important point to acknowledge, or we are talking about Palestine and Israel, because this is a settler colonial situation, this isn't a situation between of religion, of conflicts, and the right to return pinpoint jobs that this is an issue with settler colonialism, as every single settler colony throughout history has always viewed the native people as a demographic threat.

Content: Why is a key the most important position many Palestinian refugees own? The key is the most symbolic symbol to Palestinians and most specifically to Palestinian refugees, as it represents their right of return. At least 750,000 Palestinians were forced out of their homes during the ethnic cleansing of 1948, also known as the Nakhba. Zionist forces invaded historic Palestine and captured 78% of Palestinian land. Hundreds of Palestinian villages were destroyed and some 15,000 Palestinians were killed. Israel banned most Palestinian refugees from ever returning to their homes. Due to the creation of Israel taking place in such a short amount of time, we saw huge numbers of Palestinian's become refugees and they were forced to leave and flee their homes, leaving everything but behind. Except one thing, the key to their homes and they kept this key on the belief that one day they would return. There are about 6 million Palestinian refugees in the occupied West Bank, Gaza and neighbouring countries. Many still cling to the hope of returning home and the key represents that. You'll see a huge number of these Palestinian refugees still holding onto their keys of their homes from before 1948 and this become kind of this unspoken generational gift onto the next generation. But if that generation who's holding onto the key of their home at that time, if they are not physically able to live to see a decolonized Palestine and to go back to their home, they'll pass on to that key onto the next generation. Many older Palestinians still remember their lives and homes before the Nakhba took place and hope to return. I find it both heartbreaking and angering to see that we have to see yet another generation pass on these keys to their grandchildren, to their own children and it's not them themselves returning to Palestine. As a part of Qifle-Ti'at we say we want to see return within our lifetimes and we want to see our elders, not their grandchildren, not their great-great-grandchildren, but the our elders, the ones who personally had to flee from the Nakhba, we want to see them return in our lifetimes. For our founded Qifle-Ti'at in 2017 to mark 100 years of the Balfour Declaration, that's when the British government gave support for an adjouish homeland in Palestine. When we created this, we wanted a visible symbol for people to see that one of the key solutions to Palestine isn't this regurgitated, insincere rhetoric or two-state solution, but one of the key solutions in itself is our key is our right to pattern. The right to pattern lies at the heart of what should happen next when we talk about Palestine, which is decolonization, which is dismantling these really settler colonial projects. Key 48 has issued over 10,000 symbolic keys and 30 countries to raise awareness about Palestinian rights. The group has been supported by Bella Hadid and Roger Waters. And that's the most important point to acknowledge, or we are talking about Palestine and Israel, because this is a settler colonial situation, this isn't a situation between of religion, of conflicts, and the right to return pinpoint jobs that this is an issue with settler colonialism, as every single settler colony throughout history has always viewed the native people as a demographic threat.

Content: The wailing wall in Jerusalem is the most important holy site in the Jewish world. The significance of the wall is that it's the only remaining piece from the second temple of Jerusalem built over 2,000 years ago. The original temple was destroyed in 70 AD by the Romans, and all the Jewish people were exiled from the city. When they returned later on, the only remaining wall became a site of pilgrimage. It was where the Jewish people came to lament their tragic losses at the hands of the Romans, which is where it caught the name the wailing wall. The wall is immense, built of thick limestone 60 feet tall, but not everyone is convinced that the wall really was part of the temple. It's disputed with devout Jews believing it to be real, and many Arabs arguing the walls actually belong to a mosque called Al-Aqsa, a mystery year is that no one can definitively say what structure the wall belonged to.

Content: We were able to visit the western wall in the old city of Jerusalem. As an American, I've heard it called the wailing wall. However, I recently learned that that name is deravertory, and we won't be using that. This view shows the western wall with a dome of the rock and the all-ask mosque in the background. According to the Hebrew Bible, Solomon's Temple was built atop what is now known as the Temple Mount in the 10th century BCE, which makes it very important to the Jewish faith. You will notice that there is one side of the wall where women pray and the other side where men pray. They will give men Yomikas and headscarce for the women. However, if you are not praying, they do not require women to wear the headscarce. This place is also very special in Muslim tradition as well. It is believed to be the site where the Islamic prophet Muhammad ascended to Paradise. Security is very tight here as you can see, and you will be asked to go through a metal detector to enter. This is such a special place to many religions, so make sure to add this to your list.

video_description: Violence broke out overnight af the Al Aqsa mosque in Jerusalem where more than 150 Palestinians were injured. #templemount #jerusalem #palestinians
Content: Breaking overnight, violence at a holy site in Jerusalem for Muslims and Jews has injured more than 150 Palestinians and three police officers. Israeli police battled rock-throwing youths at the Al-Aksim mosque also known as Temple Mount. Thousands of Palestinians had gathered for Friday prayers in the middle of the Holy Month of Ramadan, which falls this year at the same time as Passover in Easter. A similar clash at the site last year led to an 11-day war between Israel and Hamas in Gaza.

video_description: Some call it Al Aqsa, some call it Temple Mount. The holy site in east Jerusalem is important to many faiths and it helps illustrate tensions between #Israel and #palestine.     #templemount #westernwall #alaqsa #alaqsamosque #jews #muslims #aljazeera
Content: Here's one place to know about to help you understand the Israeli-Palestinian conflict a little better. It's an occupied Easter-Russelam, and the site is holy in Judaism, Islam, and Christianity too. Muslims usually refer to it as al-Aqsa, and Jews call it Temple Mount. It's a big compound that includes the al-Aqsa mosque and this shrine called Dome of the Rock, both very important to Muslims. For Jews, this site is where two ancient temples used to be, and it's considered so holy that most Jewish religious leaders say Jews aren't allowed to pray there. Instead, they pray outside the compound at the Western Wall. Now this place isn't the news a lot because what happens there tends to spill out. One example is this visit in 2000 by Israeli politician Ariel Shahron, which triggered a Palestinian uprising called the Second Intifada. Now there's a long-standing arrangement about who can access the site and what they can do. If you've heard of status quo, that's essentially what we're talking about. And it's basically this. Now, who actually controls who visits and who prays? Well, in theory, it's an Islamic trust known as the Wakaaf, but Israeli forces control many of the gates and the security outside the compound, because Easter-Russelam is under a military occupation by Israel. And this is where all the issues come up because Israeli forces are increasingly taking control of what goes on inside the compound, like restricting Muslims, especially Palestinians from entering, and turning a blind eye to Jews openly praying there. This year a lot of people were angry when Israel's new interior minister Ben Gavir went, and it was seen as a very provocative move. So here's the thing. You've got this really holy place, thousands of years of history, and what's supposed to be an established way of doing things, but it's changing, because we're seeing two trends play out there. One, there's the growing power of the far right in Israel, people who say Jews should be able to pray at the compound, and that it should be under Israeli control. And two, Palestinians living under Israeli occupation are increasingly seeing their rights, their land, and identity being erased. And when that happens at Al-Aqsa, they really see it as a final straw. By the way, we do these explainers about news topics all the time on my show start here. In 1917, the British government, hoping to gain the support of Jewish people, issued the Balfour Declaration, promising, quote, the establishment in Palestine of a national home for the Jewish people. A bold promise considering that Palestine was still technically Ottoman as they hadn't yet lost World War I.
